Sure, but what may be a fair way to assess a piece of work is to ask if it has considered and engaged its historical and contemporary literature and context adequately, including—and especially—those that may have been ideologically opposed to its premises.

Consider, e.g., if 50 years from now "liberal" views become unacceptable to society. Would it be fair to trash the academic contributions of 1950-2050 "liberals" in 2070 because as per the current norms their views were thought to be damaging? Some balance needed in retrospect

"Normal back then" is not necessarily an excuse, but an attempt to understand rationally. Current social mores do have an impact on one's thinking. I feel its important to analyze whether someone was above or blow the mean for their era in the context of some "ism".

Back to the USA for our 8th @womeninmalaria addition today: Dr Jennifer Stevenson of @JohnsHopkinsSPH/#MachaResearchTrust. Dr Stevenson is the MRT Scientific Director, overseeing multiple #malaria & #entomology projects in Zambia. More at https://www.bovanetwork.org/users/jennifer-stevenson! #WomenInMalaria

Now to the ICMR-National Institute of Malaria Research in New Delhi (@nimr_delhi) where our 7th #WomenInMalaria addition, Poonam Singh, studies climate change & vector-borne diseases, in particular, the environmental epidemiology of #malaria vectors;

Our 6th #WomenInMalaria addition is an incredibly impressive member of the Global and Tropical Health Division at @MenziesResearch: Sophie Weston. Sophie is a Clinical Trial Monitor & Research Coordinator, working on primaquine use for P. vivax malaria: https://www.menzies.edu.au/page/Our_People/Researchers/Sophie_Weston/

Back to Europe now with our 5th #WomenInMalaria addition of the day! Elisabet Martí Coma-Cros is a Predoctoral Fellow at @ISGLOBALorg/@MESAmalaria in Barcelona, España, working on the application of nanotechnology to antimalarial drug delivery. Find her at

Our 4th @womeninmalaria addition today is Dr Robin H. Miller of the #Malaria Division at @USAID! Dr Miller is currently an AAAS Science and Technology Fellow whose expertise lies in epidemiology of emerging infectious diseases & molecular epidemiology:

Our second new @womeninmalaria addition today is Dr Lungowe Sitali of the University of Zambia (@UNZA_ZM) whose current work focusses on the effectiveness of national malaria intervention programs in preventing maternal and paediatric malaria in Zambia.

Happy New Year @womeninmalaria!! Long overdue update!- we're now at 383 #WomenInMalaria from 38 countries at https://bit.ly/2T9v0ke! Let's start by welcoming Dr Katherine de Villiers from @StellenboschUni to Twitter with the brilliant @HaemTeam handle!
